  "tips": [
    {
      "type": "lead",
      "text": "The colon and the semicolon are the marks that show structure - the quiet workhorses of careful writing. The colon sets up what follows; the semicolon joins two thoughts too close to split apart. Use them well and a reader feels the logic without ever noticing the punctuation."
    },
    {
      "type": "drop",
      "text": "Good news for your right pinky: the semicolon sits right on the home row, already under that finger - tap it, no Shift. The colon is the same key with Shift held: left pinky holds Shift, right pinky taps the key. One finger, one position, two marks."
    },
    {
      "type": "callout",
      "icon": "✍️",
      "title": "Each mark has a job",
      "text": "A colon introduces - a list, an example, a quote: like this. A semicolon links two full thoughts that belong together; it is a softer stop than a period. Use them on purpose, not for decoration."
    },
    {
      "type": "step",
      "kind": "drill",
      "target": "; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ;",
      "finger": "pink",
      "title": "The semicolon",
      "hint": "Right pinky taps the home-row key, then home. No Shift."
    },
    {
      "type": "step",
      "kind": "drill",
      "target": ": : : : : : : : : : : : : : :",
      "finger": "pink",
      "title": "The colon",
      "hint": "Left pinky holds Shift, right pinky taps the same key. Hold, tap, release."
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "Now put them where they earn their place. The lines below set up with colons and join with semicolons. Read each clause, then type it through - space after the mark, never before."
    },
    {
      "type": "pullquote",
      "text": "A semicolon is a held breath; use it when a period would say too much and a comma too little.",
      "by": "Eleanor Hayes, editor"
    },
    {
      "type": "step",
      "kind": "drill",
      "target": "note: this works; that does not. listen: be careful; the path is steep; we are close.",
      "finger": "orange",
      "title": "Structure in sentences",
      "hint": "Colon to introduce, semicolon to link. One space after each."
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "Steps done? Open the trainer below and take one clean run at the full lesson text. That run saves your progress and unlocks the next lesson."
    }
  ],
  "character_tips": {
    "anna": "Semicolon links thoughts. Colon introduces. Both belong to the right pinky.",
